<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Luganda&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Phonology">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Phonology">Phonology</span></h2>
<p>A notable feature of Luganda phonology is its <a href="/wiki/Geminate_consonant" title="Geminate consonant" class="mw-redirect">geminate consonants</a> and distinctions between <a href="/wiki/Long_vowel" title="Long vowel" class="mw-redirect">long</a> and <a href="/wiki/Short_vowel" title="Short vowel" class="mw-redirect">short</a> vowels. Speakers generally consider consonantal gemination and vowel lengthening to be two manifestations of the same effect, which they call simply "doubling" or "stressing".</p>
<p>Luganda is also a <a href="/wiki/Tonal_language" title="Tonal language" class="mw-redirect">tonal language</a>; the change in the pitch of a syllable can change the meaning of a word. For example the word <i>kabaka</i> means 'king' if all three syllables are given the same pitch. If the first syllable is high then the meaning changes to 'the little one catches' (third person singular present tense Class VI <i>ka-</i> of <i>-baka</i> 'to catch'). This feature makes Luganda a difficult language for speakers of non-tonal languages to learn. A non-native speaker has to learn the variations of pitch by prolonged listening.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Luganda&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Vowels">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Vowels">Vowels</span></h3>
<table class="IPA wikitable">
<caption>Luganda vowels</caption>
<tr>
<th></th>
<th><a href="/wiki/Front_vowel" title="Front vowel">Front</a></th>
<th><a href="/wiki/Back_vowel" title="Back vowel">Back</a></th>
</tr>
<tr align="center">
<th><a href="/wiki/Close_vowel" title="Close vowel">Close</a></th>
<td>i</td>
<td>u</td>
</tr>
<tr align="center">
<th><a href="/wiki/Close-mid_vowel" title="Close-mid vowel">Close-mid</a></th>
<td>e</td>
<td>o</td>
</tr>
<tr align="center">
<th><a href="/wiki/Open_vowel" title="Open vowel">Open</a></th>
<td colspan="2">a</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>All five vowels have two forms: <a href="/wiki/Long_vowel" title="Long vowel" class="mw-redirect">long</a> and <a href="/wiki/Short_vowel" title="Short vowel" class="mw-redirect">short</a>. The distinction is phonemic but can occur only in certain positions. After two consonants, the latter being a <a href="/wiki/Semivowel" title="Semivowel">semivowel</a>, all vowels are long. Before a <a href="/wiki/Prenasalised_consonant" title="Prenasalised consonant" class="mw-redirect">prenasalised consonant</a>, all vowels are long. Before a <a href="/wiki/Geminate_consonant" title="Geminate consonant" class="mw-redirect">geminate</a>, all vowels are short. The <a href="/wiki/Vowel_quality" title="Vowel quality" class="mw-redirect">quality</a> of a vowel is not affected by its length.</p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Luganda&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Consonants">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Consonants">Consonants</span></h3>
